questiontext.text:
The data provided in data-04.csv contains information about the record-winning times of 200 races. The data contains the following variables:

  • distance: the distance covered in miles,
  • climb: elevation climbed during the race in feet, and
  • time: the record time for race in minutes.

The following two models are proposed:

\[\begin{align}M_1: &\log_{10}(\texttt{time}_i) = \beta_0 + \beta_1 \log_{10}(\texttt{climb}_i) + \beta_2 \log_{10}(\texttt{distance}_i) + \beta_3 \log_{10}(\texttt{climb}_i) \times \log_{10}(\texttt{distance}_i) + e_{1i},\\ M_2: & \log_{10}(\texttt{time}_i) = \gamma_0 + \gamma_1\log_{10}(\texttt{distance}_i) + e_{2i},\end{align}\] $$$$ where \(i = 1, ..., 200\) and assume \(e_{1i}\sim N(0, \sigma^2), e_{2i} \sim N(0, \sigma^2)\). Fit the model using least squares method.

  1. For \(M_1\), what is the least squares estimate of the following parameters to 4 decimal places?
  • \(\hat{\beta}_0 =\) {1:NUMERICAL:=2.0401:1e-04}
  • \(\hat{\beta}_1 =\) {1:NUMERICAL:=-0.3335:1e-04}
  • \(\hat{\beta}_2 =\) {1:NUMERICAL:=-1.2174:1e-04}
  • \(\hat{\beta}_3 =\) {1:NUMERICAL:=0.6243:1e-04}
  1. What is the sum of the squares of the residuals for \(M_1\) and \(M_2\), respectively, to 4 decimal places?
    \(M_1\): {1:NUMERICAL:=2.8545:1e-04} and \(M_2\): {1:NUMERICAL:=3.1212:1e-04}.
  2. You want to draw a scatter plot with the fitted model \(M_2\) superimposed on it like the plot below.

Complete the code below to draw the above plot.

library(ggplot2)
ggplot(df, aes(distance, time)) +
  geom_point() + 
  geom_ {1:SHORTANSWER:%100%smooth}(method = lm, formula = y ~ x, se = FALSE) +
   {1:SHORTANSWER:%100%scale_x_log10}() + 
  scale_y_log10()

generalfeedback.text:
The two models are fitted in R like below:

df <- read.csv("data-04.csv")
fit1 <- lm(log10(time) ~ log10(climb) * log10(distance), data = df)
fit2 <- lm(log10(time) ~ log10(distance), data = df)
coef(fit1)
sum(fit1$residuals^2)
sum(fit2$residuals^2)

When superimposing the model, you need the \(\log_{10}\) scale transformations like below.

library(ggplot2)
ggplot(df, aes(distance, time)) +
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(method = lm, formula = y ~ x, se = FALSE) +
  scale_x_log10() + 
  scale_y_log10()
  1. 2.0401
  2. -0.3335
  3. -1.2174
  4. 0.6243
  5. 2.8545
  6. 3.1212
  7. smooth
  8. scale_x_log10
